  "local_port": 35676,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Why do people get headaches, puffy eyes and red nose after crying?",
  "response": "Crying can lead to several physical effects on the body, including headaches, puffy eyes, and a red nose. Here's why these symptoms occur:\n\n1. **Headaches:**\n   - **Tension and Muscle Strain:** Crying often involves a lot of emotional and physical tension. The muscles in the face, head, and neck can become strained, leading to tension headaches.\n   - **Dehydration:** Crying results in the loss of fluids, which can contribute to dehydration. Dehydration can cause or worsen headaches.\n   - **Sinus Pressure:** Crying can increase mucus production, leading to sinus pressure and congestion, which can also cause headaches.\n\n2. **Puffy Eyes:**\n   - **Increased Blood Flow:** When you cry, the blood vessels around your eyes dilate, causing more blood to flow to the area. This increased blood flow can lead to swelling and puffiness.\n   - **Fluid Retention:** The release of certain hormones and chemicals during crying can cause the body to retain fluid around the eyes, contributing to puffiness.\n\n3. **Red Nose:**\n   - **Increased Blood Flow:** Similar to the eyes, the blood vessels in the nose can dilate during crying, leading to a red appearance.\n   - **Irritation and Rubbing:** The act of crying often involves rubbing or blowing the nose, which can cause irritation and further redness.\n   - **Mucus Production:** Crying can stimulate the production of mucus, which can lead to a stuffy or runny nose, contributing to the red appearance.\n\nThese symptoms are generally temporary and should resolve on their own within a few hours. If they persist or are severe, it may be wise to consult a healthcare professional.",
